as a sex worker and was treated for chlamydia two months ago. All other screening tests for sexually transmitted infections, including syphilis, were negative at this time. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. All initial antenatal screening tests are normal. An ultrasound scan confirms a viable intrauterine pregnancy of 10 weeks and two days gestation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate timing for her next syphilis screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["12 weeks gestation","20 weeks gestation","24 weeks gestation","28 weeks gestation","36 weeks gestation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple risk factors for sexually transmitted infections including sex work and recent chlamydia infection. While her initial antenatal screening tests are normal, she requires additional surveillance throughout pregnancy. Despite her increased risk factors all patients should be screened for syphilis at both booking, 26-28 weeks and 36 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E28 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended timing for repeat syphilis screening in all pregnant people, followed by a third test at 36 weeks. This timing allows detection and treatment of infections acquired during pregnancy before significant fetal complications develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUntreated syphilis in pregnancy can lead to serious complications including stillbirth, preterm birth, low birth weight, and congenital syphilis. The latter can cause multiple system abnormalities including bone deformities, neurological problems, and organ dysfunction. Early detection through appropriate screening intervals allows prompt treatment with penicillin, which is highly effective at preventing these complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All pregnant people should be screened for syphilis at the first antenatal visit, 26-28 weeks and 36 weeks of pregnancy","Risk factors for sexually transmitted infections include sex work, previous STIs, and limited antenatal care."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases. Management of perinatal infections. 2014. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/ASID-Management-Perinatal-Infections.pdf","Queensland Clinical Guidelines. Syphilis and pregnancy. Guideline No. MN24.44-V7-R29. Queensland Health. December 2024. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0035/736883/g-sip.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12461"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T18:00:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-16T09:39:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4969"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i